Judge Robert Wier has the opportunity to continue serving his community as a U.S. District Court Judge, and I am grateful for his willingness to dedicate himself further to the people of #Kentucky and this nation.

Rebecca Grady Jennings is eminently qualified to assume the role of a judge. She has experience in a wide-array of matters – from intellectual property litigation to employment litigation to class actions. 
#Kentucky

With experience as both a litigator & a transactional attorney, Claria Horn Boom will bring a breadth of experience to the federal bench.  That outlook,plus her deep ties to the legal community in #Kentucky, will serve her well as a judge for both the Eastern & Western Districts.

Watch @SenateMajLdr deliver remarks before @senjudiciary in support of Claria Horn Boom of Lexington, Rebecca Grady Jennings of Louisville, & Magistrate Judge Robert Wier of Versailles, @POTUS nominees to serve as federal district court judges in #Kentucky http://bit.ly/2z4HuRy
According to @taxfoundation study, families in my home state of #Kentucky could see a, ‘boost to after-tax incomes for middle-income families,’ of nearly $2,000.pic.twitter.com/npqNaaz3w1
We want to take more money out of Washington’s pockets and put more in the pockets of the middle class. That’s why we’re pursuing #taxreform.

For small business owners in #Kentucky – and throughout the country – we want to make it easier to grow, invest, and hire. For families everywhere, we want to make taxes lower, simpler, and fairer.
#TaxReform
#TaxReform Will Deliver Relief To Small Businesses And The Middle Classhttp://bit.ly/2zYbui4

Today, I had opportunity to meet w/ a number of #Kentucky small business owners & workers to hear from them about importance of #TaxReform. We discussed how this effort can help provide relief to small businesses & middle-class families by making taxes lower, simpler, & fairer.
According to @taxfoundation study, families in my home state of Kentucky could see a, “boost to after-tax incomes for middle-income families,” of nearly $2,000.
